  "prompt": "How good/bad are TCS holiday homes? Are friends from work allowed to share the same room?",
  "response": "Let's break down TCS holiday homes, addressing both their general quality and the rules around sharing rooms.\n\n**General Quality of TCS Holiday Homes:**\n\nThe quality of TCS holiday homes can vary significantly. Here's a realistic overview:\n\n*   **Factors Affecting Quality:**\n    *   **Location:** Prime locations (hill stations, beaches) tend to be better maintained and more popular.\n    *   **Age:** Older properties might show wear and tear. Newer ones are generally better.\n    *   **Management:** The on-site management team makes a big difference in cleanliness, service, and overall upkeep.\n    *   **Season:** Peak season can put a strain on resources, potentially impacting service quality.\n\n*   **Common Feedback (Based on General Trends - Actual Experiences Vary):**\n    *   **Pros:**\n        *   **Affordable:** A major draw.  They're often significantly cheaper than comparable hotels or resorts.\n        *   **Good Locations:** TCS often has properties in desirable tourist destinations.\n        *   **Basic Amenities:** Generally, expect basic amenities like beds, linens, towels, basic kitchen equipment (if applicable), and sometimes a TV.\n        *   **Safe & Secure:**  Security is usually decent.\n    *   **Cons:**\n        *   **Maintenance:**  This is the most common complaint.  Some properties can be poorly maintained.\n        *   **Cleanliness:** Cleanliness can be inconsistent.  Some are spotless, others less so.\n        *   **Amenities:** Don't expect luxury.  It's usually functional, not fancy.\n        *   **Booking Process:** The booking system can sometimes be cumbersome (availability, confirmation).\n        *   **Service:**  Service levels can vary greatly depending on the staff and location.\n\n*   **Expectation Management:**\n    *   Treat it like a budget-friendly option. Don't go in expecting a luxury resort experience.\n    *   Read reviews and ask colleagues who have stayed at the specific location you're considering.  Personal recommendations are invaluable.\n    *   Carry your own toiletries, and perhaps some extra cleaning supplies, just in case.\n    *   Take photos of any pre-existing damage upon arrival and report it immediately to avoid being held responsible.\n\n**Sharing Rooms with Friends from Work:**\n\n*   **This is generally ALLOWED, but with caveats.**\n\n*   **Key Considerations and Potential Restrictions:**\n\n    *   **Booking Capacity:** The most important factor. A room designated for \"2 adults\" can generally accommodate two adults. If a room says \"family of 4,\" then it would be acceptable to have four adults.\n    *   **TCS Policy:** TCS's internal policy will be the ultimate authority. Check the specific rules and regulations for holiday home bookings on the TCS intranet or employee portal.  Look for sections about:\n        *   Guest policies\n        *   Occupancy limits\n        *   Rules regarding non-family members\n    *   **Common Sense:** Be respectful of other guests. Avoid excessive noise or disruptive behavior.\n    *   **Officially Enrolled Guests:** Make sure all guests that are not part of your immediate family are enrolled as guests, and they have to agree with the TCS policy of the property you are staying at.\n    *   **Inform the Management:** It's generally a good idea to inform the on-site management that you're sharing the room with a colleague. This avoids misunderstandings later.\n\n**How to Find Out Definitively:**\n\n1.  **TCS Intranet/Employee Portal:** This is your primary source. Search for \"holiday homes,\" \"guest house rules,\" or similar terms.\n2.  **Contact TCS HR or Travel Department:** If the information isn't clear online, contact your HR department or the team responsible for holiday home bookings. They can provide official clarification.\n3.  **Speak to Colleagues:**  Ask colleagues who have used the holiday homes if they've shared rooms with friends and what the process was.\n4.  **Contact the Holiday Home Directly:**  Call the specific holiday home you're interested in. The on-site manager can answer your questions about room sharing.\n\n**In summary:** TCS holiday homes are generally a budget-friendly option, but quality can be inconsistent. Sharing rooms with friends is usually allowed, as long as you adhere to occupancy limits and follow TCS's policies.  Always verify the specific rules and regulations before booking.\n",
